# ERP Drawer — Child Dialog Modal Blocking Standard

## The Bug This Prevents

Both the ERP drawer (`Sheet`) and child form dialogs (`Dialog`) use `@base-ui/react/dialog`
at the same `z-50` z-index. Base UI's nested modal stack does **not** prevent the Sheet
(parent drawer) from receiving pointer and keyboard events when a child `Dialog` is open.

This was fixed in **ERP BASE 002F.5A.3X** (2026-06-14).

Without the fix, users can:
- Switch parent tabs while a child form is open
- Edit parent fields through the dialog
- Trigger parent Save / Save & Close
- Open a second child form while one is already open

## The Fix Pattern

Use the browser-native **`inert` HTML attribute** on the drawer's inner content wrapper.

`inert` makes an element and all its descendants:
- Non-interactive (all pointer events ignored)
- Non-focusable (keyboard cannot reach the subtree)
- Hidden from accessibility tools

**Why this works without blocking the Dialog**: Child `Dialog` components render via
`DialogPortal` to `document.body` — outside the `SheetContent` DOM. `inert` on the
SheetContent wrapper does NOT affect the Dialog.

---

## Required Implementation for Any Drawer with Child Dialogs

### Step 1 — Parent Drawer: Track child dialog state and apply `inert`

```tsx
// In the parent drawer component:
const [childDialogOpen, setChildDialogOpen] = useState(false);
const handleChildOpen = useCallback((open: boolean) => setChildDialogOpen(open), []);

// In JSX — wrap all interactive drawer content:
<ERPDrawerForm ...>
  <div inert={childDialogOpen || undefined} className="contents">
    <ERPDrawerSectionNav ... />
    <form ...>
      <ERPDrawerBody>
        <SomeTab partyId={...} onChildOpen={handleChildOpen} />
        {/* ... other tabs ... */}
      </ERPDrawerBody>
      <ERPFormFooter ... />
    </form>
  </div>
</ERPDrawerForm>
```

- Use `className="contents"` so the wrapper is invisible to layout (`display: contents`).
- The `inert` attribute is `true` (present) when any child dialog is open, `undefined`
  (absent) otherwise.
- Dialogs that live OUTSIDE `ERPDrawerForm` (e.g. duplicate detection dialogs rendered
  after the closing tag) do NOT need to be inside the `inert` wrapper.

### Step 2 — Each Tab with a Child Dialog: Add `onChildOpen` prop + `setDialogOpen` helper

```tsx
// Props type:
type MyTabProps = {
  partyId: number;
  disabled?: boolean;
  onChildOpen?: (open: boolean) => void;  // ← add this
};

// In the component:
export function MyTab({ partyId, disabled, onChildOpen }: MyTabProps) {
  const [isDialogOpen, setIsDialogOpen] = useState(false);

  // ← add this helper — replaces direct setIsDialogOpen calls:
  const setDialogOpen = (open: boolean) => {
    setIsDialogOpen(open);
    onChildOpen?.(open);
  };

  // openAdd / openEdit: use setDialogOpen(true)
  const openAdd = () => {
    setForm({ ...emptyForm });
    setDialogOpen(true);       // ← not setIsDialogOpen
  };

  // handleSubmit: use setDialogOpen(false) on success
  const handleSubmit = async () => {
    const result = await saveAction(...);
    if (result.success) {
      setDialogOpen(false);    // ← not setIsDialogOpen
    }
  };

  return (
    <>
      {/* ... table / list ... */}

      {/* Dialog: use setDialogOpen in onOpenChange */}
      <Dialog open={isDialogOpen} onOpenChange={setDialogOpen}>  {/* ← not setIsDialogOpen */}
        <DialogContent>
          {/* ... form fields ... */}
          <DialogFooter>
            <Button onClick={() => setDialogOpen(false)}>Cancel</Button>  {/* ← not setIsDialogOpen */}
            <Button onClick={handleSubmit}>Save</Button>
          </DialogFooter>
        </DialogContent>
      </Dialog>
    </>
  );
}
```

---

## Rules Summary

1. **Every tab component that opens a child Dialog MUST accept `onChildOpen?: (open: boolean) => void`.**
2. **Every tab MUST define a `setDialogOpen` helper** that calls both `setIsDialogOpen` and `onChildOpen?.(open)`.
3. **Never call `setIsDialogOpen` directly** in openAdd, openEdit, handleSubmit, or Cancel — always use `setDialogOpen`.
4. **The parent drawer MUST wrap interactive content in `<div inert={childDialogOpen || undefined}>`.**
5. **Dialog.onOpenChange MUST use `setDialogOpen`** (not `setIsDialogOpen`) so Esc and outside-click also notify the parent.
6. **Do NOT apply `inert` to the Dialog itself** — the Dialog renders in a portal to body and is unaffected by `inert` on the drawer content.

---

## Why `inert` and Not `pointer-events-none`

| Approach | Blocks pointer | Blocks keyboard | Blocks focus | Accessible |
|----------|---------------|-----------------|--------------|-----------|
| `pointer-events-none` (CSS) | ✅ | ❌ | ❌ | ❌ |
| `disabled` on each element | ✅ | ✅ | ✅ | partial |
| `inert` (HTML attribute) | ✅ | ✅ | ✅ | ✅ |

`inert` is the only option that fully blocks ALL forms of interaction with a single attribute,
on the whole subtree, without modifying individual child components.

## React 19 Note

React 19 natively supports the `inert` boolean HTML attribute on all elements.
Use `inert={condition || undefined}` — when condition is `false`, `|| undefined` removes
the attribute entirely (React does not render `inert={false}` as an attribute).

```tsx
// ✅ Correct
<div inert={childDialogOpen || undefined}>

// ✅ Also valid in React 19
<div inert={childDialogOpen ? true : undefined}>

// ❌ Wrong — renders inert="" unconditionally
<div inert>

// ❌ Wrong — renders inert="false" (still inert!) in some React versions
<div inert={false}>
```

